'''Saoyú-ʔehdacho''' (also known as '''Sahoyue-Edacho''', '''Sahoyúé-§ehdacho''', '''Saoyú and Æehdacho''' and '''Grizzly Bear Mountain and Scented Grass Hills''') is a [[cultural landscape]] in the [[Northwest Territories]], [[Canada]], comprising two [[peninsula]]s in [[Great Bear Lake]].<ref name="CRHP">{{CRHP|13033|Sahoyúé-§ehdacho National Historic Site of Canada|11 October 2013}}</ref> The site has great cultural and spiritual significance for the [[Sahtu people]],<ref name="Backgrounder">{{cite web|title=Backgrounder|url=http://www.pc.gc.ca/APPS/CP-NR/release_e.asp?bgid=901&andor1=bg|work=Signing of Memorandum of Understanding for Permanent Protection of Sahoyúé §ehdacho National Historic Site of Canada|publisher=[[Parks Canada]]|accessdate=11 October 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6KIUvQmKn|archivedate=11 October 2013|date=11 March 2007}}</ref> as it is considered sacred land and it features prominently in their [[oral history|oral histories]].<ref name="Outspan">{{cite web|title=Background Information and Preliminary Assessment|url=http://www.nwtpas.ca/areas/document-2006-sahoyue-socioeconomic-full.pdf|work=The Outspan Group Inc. 1 Socio-Economic Assessment of the Sahoyúé-§ehdacho Candidate Protected Area|publisher=The Outspan Group Inc.|accessdate=15 October 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6KO4YeYLn|archivedate=15 October 2013|page=9|year=2006}}</ref>
==Natural and cultural heritage== Saoyú-ʔehdacho is {{convert|5587|km2}} in size, approximately the size of the province of [[Prince Edward Island]],<ref name="Backgrounder"/> and consists of two peninsulas: Saoyú (Grizzly Bear Mountain) and ʔehdacho (Scented Grass Hills).<ref name="Outspan"/> The peninsulas are both characterized by flat summits, approximately {{convert|725|and|650|m}} [[Sea level|above sea level]] respectively. The perimeters of both promontories feature a series of raised beaches, formed by the [[post-glacial rebound]], which contain the majority of the known evidence of human occupation of the lands, including archaeological resources related to [[Pre-Columbian era|pre-contact]] occupation from over 5000 years ago.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sahoyúé-§ehdacho: Commemorative Integrity Statement|url=http://www.nwtpas.ca/areas/document-2004-sahoyue-commemorativeintegrity-summary.pdf|publisher=Northwest Territories Protected Areas Strategy|accessdate=15 October 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6KOWTT4N3|archivedate=15 October 2013|year=2004}}</ref>
==National Historic Site== [[File:Bear Mountain, Great Bear Lake, Northwest Territories.jpg|thumb|left|Grizzly Bear Mountain in the 1920s]] Saoyú-ʔehdacho was designated a [[National Historic Sites of Canada|National Historic Site]] in 1997, on the basis that the landscape, its cultural resources (including graves, trails and cabins) and its associated oral histories contribute to an understanding of the origin, spiritual values, lifestyle and land-use of the Sahtu [[Dene]].<ref name="CRHP"/> In 2001 and 2005, the federal government enacted withdrawal orders under the ''Territorial Lands Act'', prohibiting the registration of new mineral claims or other third party interests against the Saoyú-ʔehdacho lands. In 2007, [[Parks Canada]] entered into an agreement with the Déline First Nation to permanently protect and cooperatively manage the site, with surface title to the [[Crown land]]s portion of the site (constituting 80% of the overall land) transferred to Parks Canada from [[Aboriginal Affairs and Northern Development Canada]] in 2009.<ref name="Backgrounder"/><ref>{{cite web|title=News release|url=http://www.pc.gc.ca/APPS/CP-NR/release_e.asp?id=1078&andor1=nr|work=Canada's New Government Takes Significant Step to Protect Major National Historic Site in the North|publisher=[[Parks Canada]]|accessdate=11 October 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6KIUyWz3T|archivedate=11 October 2013|date=11 March 2007}}</ref> In 2011, an [[Order in Council]] increased the legal protection for Crown-owned portions of the site by applying regulatory protections under the [[National Parks Act (Canada)|National Parks Act]] to the lands.<ref>{{cite web|title=Canada Gazette|url=http://www.gazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p2/2012/2012-01-04/html/sor-dors319-eng.html|work=P.C. 2011-1670 (Order Amending the National Historic Sites of Canada Order)|publisher=[[Public Works and Government Services Canada]]|accessdate=15 October 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6KOV8yDd3|archivedate=15 October 2013|date=15 December 2011}}</ref>
Saoyú-ʔehdacho is the largest National Historic Site of Canada in land area.<ref name="Prentice news release">{{cite web|title=News Release|url=http://www.pc.gc.ca/APPS/CP-NR/release_e.asp?id=1292&andor1=nr|work=Government of Canada Announces the Protection of Canada's Largest National Historic Site|publisher=[[Parks Canada]]|accessdate=11 October 2013}}</ref> Saoyú-ʔehdacho is also: *the first National Historic Site both designated and acquired on the basis of consultation with [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Aboriginal peoples]]; *the first National Historic Site in [[Northern Canada]] cooperatively managed by Parks Canada and an aboriginal group; *the first National Historic Site in the Northwest Territories in which Parks Canada is involved in the administration; and *the first cultural landscape in Northern Canada commemorated by the [[Government of Canada]].<ref name="Backgrounder"/><ref name="Prentice news release"/>
Saoyú-ʔehdacho is also the first site to be protected under the territorial government's Protected Areas Strategy, a consultative process created with the involvement of the federal and territorial governments, aboriginal groups, environmental groups and industry, with the objective of establishing a network of [[protected areas]] across the Northwest Territories.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nwtpas.ca/index.asp|title=Northwest Territories Protected Areas Strategy|publisher=Northwest Territories Protected Areas Strategy|accessdate=15 October 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6KOYVAojv|archivedate=15 October 2013}}</ref>
==Name== In the [[Slavey language]], "Saoyú" means "belonging to the bear" and "ʔehdacho" means "big point".<ref>{{cite web|title=Sahoyúé- § ehdacho Working Group Final Report|url=http://www.nwtpas.ca/areas/document-2007-sahoyue-workinggroup-report.pdf|publisher=The Sahoyúé- § ehdacho Working Group|accessdate=24 October 2013|archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6Kblo8kD7|archivedate=24 October 2013|page=3|date=27 November 2007}}</ref>
When the site was first designated a National Historic Site in 1997, it was named Scented Grass Hills and Grizzly Bear Mountain. It was subsequently renamed Sahoyúé-§ehdacho, and again renamed to Saoyú-Æehdacho in June 2008 in an attempt to better reflect the Slavey name for the site. In June 2010, the cooperative management board for the site, made up of representatives of Parks Canada, the Déline Renewable Resources Council and the Déline Land Corporation, adopted the spelling Saoyú-ʔehdacho. The Status of Designation Committee of the [[Historic Sites and Monuments Board of Canada|national Historic Sites and Monuments Board]] approved the official name change for the National Historic Site in October 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Order Amending the National Historic Sites of Canada Order|url=http://www.gazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2011/2011-04-02/html/reg5-eng.html|work=[[Canada Gazette]]|publisher=[[Government of Canada]]|accessdate=2 December 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304051223/http://www.gazette.gc.ca/rp-pr/p1/2011/2011-04-02/html/reg5-eng.html|archivedate=4 March 2016|dead-url=no|location=Footnote 1|date=2 April 2011}}</ref>
