{{Infobox Scottish island |location_map=Scotland Outer Hebrides |caption=Stac Levenish shown within the Outer Hebrides |coordinates = {{coord|57.792|-8.510|display=inline}} |GridReference=NF133966 |official_name= Stac Levenish |celtic name= Stac Leibhinis |norse name= |meaning of name= |area= {{convert|24280|m²|sqft|-1|abbr=on}} |area rank= |highest elevation= {{convert|62|m|ft|0|abbr=on}} |Population=0 |population rank= |main settlement= |island group=[[St Kilda, Scotland|St Kilda]] |local authority=[[Outer Hebrides]] |references=<ref>{{NRS1C}}</ref><ref name=Smith>{{Haswell-Smith}}</ref><ref name=OS18>{{cite map|title=Ordnance Survey: Landranger map sheet 18 ''Sound of Harris (North Uist, Taransay & St Kilda)''|ISBN= 9780319231272 |publisher=Ordnance Survey|date=2008}}</ref> }}
[[File:Staclevenish.jpg|left|thumb|Stac Levenish cliff's face silhouette]]
'''Stac Levenish''' or '''Stac Leibhinis''' (sometimes simply called '''Levenish'''/'''Leibhinis''') is a [[sea stack]] in the [[St Kilda, Scotland|St Kilda]] [[archipelago]] in [[Scotland]]. Lying {{convert|2.5|km|1|abbr=off}} off Village Bay on [[Hirta]], it is part of the rim of an extinct volcano that includes [[Dùn, St Kilda|Dùn]], Ruaival and Mullach Sgar.<ref name=Smith/>
The stack is {{convert|62|m|ft|0|abbr=out}} high. Its north cliff appears to have the profile of a human face, visible when travelling to St Kilda from the east. The [[skerry]] of Na Bodhan lies to the north east.
[[File:Dun, St Kilda.jpg|thumb|300px|left|[[Dùn, St Kilda|Dùn]] from Ruaival with Stac Levenish in the background at left.]] [[File:St_Kilda_map_with_Gaelic.PNG|thumb|The St Kilda archipelago]]
The stack was climbed recreationally in the early 1900s; [[Norman Heathcote]] mentions a moderately difficult ascent in 1900, as part of a climbing expedition that also included an ascent of [[Stac Lee]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Heathcote | first = Norman | title = Climbing in St Kilda | journal = Scottish Mountaineering Club Journal | volume = 6 | issue = | pages = 146–151 | publisher = [[Scottish Mountaineering Club]] | location = | date = 1901 | url = https://books.google.com/?id=LhZB5an6mnwC | accessdate = 8 February 2009}}</ref>
